****<br>
woonx: I think you might be the one who doesnt understand focus coding really. Yes, spells have certain focus items attached to them, but the focus effects ARE different. The effect from the GoDS gives (next to other stats?) about 1000 extra hp's to the pet. The focus staffs certainly dont do that, at least I have never read about it.<br>
****<br>
<br>
Considering I have those gloves and you don't, I would tend to believe my own experience over the &quot;I've heard XXX so it's must be true&quot; side. <br>
<br>
Simple way to proove it to you, ask a mage (with gloves) to summon an epic pet without gloves. It will be level 49. Then ask him to put the gloves and summon epic again, it will be level 50. Then ask him to summon 61 air pet, it will be 60. Then ask him to summon 61 air pet with gloves equiped, it will STILL be 60. The same focus items having different effect on different pets = obvious proof that the focus side is related to the spell, not the item itself.<br>
<br>
If you want more proof, log in to my server. I will summon a lvl 60 water pet with water staff, then have a wizard kill it and see how much damage it took. Then I'll summon one for you with gloves instead of staff. You'll find out as I have that both items give the EXACT same result on the same spell.<br>
<br>
Yes there is a difference between the focus a staff will give to a 57-60 pet versus what the gloves will do on a 61-65 pet. But the same difference exist between the focus given by gloves on 57-60 pet and the same gloves on a lvl 61-65 pet (or even epic for that matter). Another obvious proof that focus is related to spell, and not the item.<br>
<br>
If you still not convinced, nothing ever will make you see the light.<br>
